\begin{abstract} 
The subset sum problem (SSP), a fundamental NP-Hard computational problem, has garnered extensive research attention due to its critical applications in cryptography, number theory, and complexity theory. While traditional approaches such as the classical backtracking algorithm provide viable solutions, their exponential time complexity presents significant computational limitations, particularly for large-scale instances. Despite substantial theoretical contributions to SSP analysis, efficient enumeration techniques for generating comprehensive solution sets remain underexplored.

Many real-world instances of SSP exhibit additive structure, where the number of unique subset sums $U$ is much smaller than $2^n$. In such cases, multiple subsets may sum to the same value, resulting in collisions. Recent work by Jesus Salas~\cite{salas2025adaptive} introduced an adaptive, structure-aware solver that deterministically enumerates only the distinct subset sums, achieving a runtime of $\tilde{O}(U)$ when $U \ll 2^n$. However, their approach is not designed for enumeration of all subsets that yield a given target sum.

We present an enhanced deterministic algorithmic framework specifically designed for structured inputs where subset sum collisions are prevalent. Our approach extends beyond single subset verification or enumeration to comprehensively enumerate all possible subsets satisfying the SSP constraints. The proposed solution integrates dynamic programming principles with length-constant enumeration techniques and recursive enumeration strategy. Unlike randomized approaches that sacrifice solution guarantees for speed, our deterministic framework ensures complete and exact enumeration.Empirical results and theoretical insights demonstrate its competitiveness, particularly in settings where existing algorithms fall short of exhaustive enumeration.
\end{abstract}


