\section{Introduction}

The \emph{Subset Sum Problem} (SSP) stands as a paradigmatic challenge in theoretical computer science, with far-reaching implications for fields such as cryptography, combinatorial optimization, and computational complexity theory. \textbf{Formally, given a set of $n$ integers and a target value $T$, the SSP asks whether there exists a subset whose elements sum precisely to $T$.} This deceptively simple formulation underpins a host of practical applications, ranging from cryptographic key analysis to resource allocation and partitioning problems.

While the classical decision variant of SSP---determining whether at least one solution exists---is a cornerstone example of NP-completeness, a deeper computational challenge arises in the \emph{enumeration} setting: listing \emph{all} subsets that satisfy the sum constraint. Enumerative versions of SSP not only amplify the computational burden but are also essential in scenarios where understanding the entire solution space is critical, such as exhaustive cryptanalysis, multi-objective optimization, and scientific modeling of feasible configurations.

