\subsection{Related Work}
\label{subsec:related}

\paragraph{Classical Exact and Deterministic Algorithms.}  
The meet-in-the-middle framework by Horowitz and Sahni~\cite{horowitz1974computing} remains a primary exact algorithm for Subset Sum, operating in \(O(2^{n/2})\) time and space. Koiliaris and Xu later introduced a faster pseudopolynomial-time algorithm~\cite{koiliaris2015faster}, which computes all achievable subset sums in \(\tilde O(\min\{\sqrt{n}u, u^{4/3}, \sigma\})\) time, where \(u\) is the maximum sum and \(\sigma\) the total input sum.

\paragraph{Pseudopolynomial and Randomized Methods.}  
Schroeppel and Shamir~\cite{schroeppel1981turing} refined MITM with a space–time tradeoff, improving space to \(O(2^{n/4})\). Bringmann’s algorithm achieves near-linear pseudopolynomial time \(O(nT)\) or \(\tilde O(n + T)\) under certain density regimes~\cite{bringmann2017subset}. Jin et al.~\cite{jin2020fast} further advanced low-space randomized algorithms that operate in \(\tilde O(nt)\) time using only logarithmic space.

\paragraph{Dense and Structure-Aware Subset Sum.}  
Recent work by Bringmann and Wellnitz~\cite{bringmann2020dense} develops near-linear algorithms tailored to dense instances (e.g., when the element range is polynomially related to \(n\)). These results leverage structural properties like additivity and collision frequency to improve upon worst-case bounds.

\paragraph{Collision-Aware Enumeration.}  
Salas’s recent arXiv preprint~\cite{salas2025adaptive} introduces a structure-aware solver that enumerates only \emph{distinct} subset sums (not all subsets), using a double meet-in-the-middle approach, dynamic programming, and combinatorial tree compression. It achieves \(\tilde O(U)\) runtime when the number of unique sums \(U \ll 2^n\) and demonstrates practical speedups on collision-rich inputs.


\paragraph{Positioning of Our Work.}
Most prior research on the Subset Sum Problem stops at the \emph{decision/search} level—determining whether a solution exists or, at best, returning a single witness (often via space–time trade-offs or randomised techniques).  There has been very little research that addresses the need to enumerate \emph{all} solution subsets, especially in dense instances where many different subsets collide to the same sum.  Our contribution closes this gap:

\begin{enumerate}[leftmargin=2em]
    \item \textbf{Complete Enumeration.}  
          The algorithm outputs \emph{every} subset whose elements sum to a target \(T\), enabling exhaustive cryptanalytic and combinatorial analyses far beyond what decision or single-witness methods can support.

    \item \textbf{Instance-Adaptive Efficiency.}  
          Running time and memory grow with \(U\),the number of distinct achievable sums rather than with the full power-set size \(2^{N}\).  Consequently, the method is highly effective on \emph{dense} or collision-rich inputs where \(U \ll 2^{N/2}\).

    \item \textbf{Constant-Bound Duplication.}  
          Through size-restricted dynamic programming and a four-way complement merge, we prove that any subset can be produced at most four times, keeping enumeration overhead firmly under control.
\end{enumerate}
    

Together, these properties yield the first practical and provably efficient framework for \emph{complete subset enumeration} in dense Subset Sum instances, contributing to the field beyond the decision-oriented focus of earlier work.



\subsection{Gap in the Literature: Efficient Full Enumeration}

Despite these advances, the task of \emph{systematically enumerating every solution subset} for SSP has received comparatively little attention. Most algorithmic efforts have focused on decision and search variants, returning either a single solution or verifying existence.Yet in many applied settings, an efficient and comprehensive enumeration is essential.

\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Cryptanalysis:} where the full preimage space must be mapped;
    \item \textbf{Combinatorial optimization:} where one compares all feasible solutions or seeks multi-modal optima;
    \item \textbf{Scientific computing:} where enumerating all valid states illuminates structural properties,
\end{itemize}

. Existing enumeration methods are often either exponential in practice or insufficiently exploit the structure and redundancy present in specific input sets.

