\section{Subset Sum Enumeration for an Arbitrary Set of $N$ Numbers}

Given an arbitrary set of $N$ positive integers $S = \{a_1, a_2, \ldots, a_N\}$, enumerating all subsets that sum to a target $T$ is, in general, computationally challenging due to the exponential number of possible subsets. To address this, we employ a classic meet-in-the-middle (MITM) strategy, which partitions the input and leverages dynamic programming with efficient state compression. Our approach is particularly effective when the number of unique subset sums, denoted $u$, is much smaller than $2^N$ - that is, when \emph{collisions} are frequent, and many distinct subsets yield the same sum.

\subsubsection*{2.1 Algorithm Overview}

The meet-in-the-middle paradigm divides $S$ into two nearly equal halves:
\[
S_L = \{a_1, \ldots, a_{\lfloor N/2 \rfloor}\}, \quad
S_R = \{a_{\lfloor N/2 \rfloor + 1}, \ldots, a_N\}.
\]
For a given target sum $T$, we independently enumerate all achievable subset sums for each half, then search for complementary pairs $(\text{sum}_L, \text{sum}_R)$ such that $\text{sum}_L + \text{sum}_R = T$. Rather than explicitly storing all $2^{N/2}$ subset sums in each half, we utilize hash maps that stores the information for each unique sum. This design is crucial for both memory efficiency and practical runtime, especially when many subsets collide to the same value.


\subsubsection*{2.2 State Representation and Data Structures}

To efficiently track and reconstruct subsets, we maintain hash maps $\mathcal{H}_L$ and $\mathcal{H}_R$ for the left and right partitions, respectively. Each entry in the hash map records the minimal information needed for backtracking. The hash table $ \mathcal H_\text{L}$ and $\mathcal H_R$ stores the following information for their corresponding half.
\[
\mathcal{H}[\text{sum}] = (\text{max\_suffix\_index}, \text{min\_count})
\]
where:
\begin{itemize}
    \item $\mathcal{H}$ can be either $\mathcal{H}_L$ or $\mathcal{H}_R$ corresponding to the two halves $\mathcal{S}_L$ and $\mathcal{S}_R$ respectively.
    \item \texttt{sum}: An achievable sum from a subset of the current half.
    \item \texttt{max\_suffix\_index}: The largest index such that the sum can be formed using only elements from this index onward.This helps in pruning search space while enumerating the subsets.
    \item \texttt{min\_count}: The minimal cardinality among all subsets that achieve \texttt{sum} for the given suffix. By maintaining this information, we restrict enumeration to subsets of size at most $\lceil |S_L|/2 \rceil$ in the left half and $\lceil |S_R|/2 \rceil$ in the right half.
\end{itemize}
 

\paragraph{Collision Advantage and Unique Subset Sums.}
When the input set $S$ has many repeated or structurally similar elements, the number of unique subset sums $U$ can be orders of magnitude smaller than the total number of subsets $2^N$. In these cases, the dynamic programming (DP) hash tables $\mathcal{H}_L$ and $\mathcal{H}_R$ remain small, enabling fast lookups, updates, and backtracking. Our approach thus scales gracefully when $U \ll 2^N$, and its performance is directly tied to this parameter.

Notably, the total number of DP entries is proportional to the number of unique achievable sums $U$ in each half, rather than the worst-case $2^{N/2}$.

\subsubsection*{2.3 Dynamic Programming Construction}

The DP hash map for each half is constructed as shown below. Note that $\mathcal S_\text{half}$ can either be $ \mathcal S_\text{L}$ or $\mathcal S_R$, and the DP hash table is computed independently for both of the halves, and stored in $ \mathcal H_\text{L}$ and $\mathcal H_R$ respectively.

\begin{algorithm}[H]
\caption{BuildDPHalf: construct DP hash map for one partition (no size constrained yet)}
\label{alg:build_dp_half}
\begin{algorithmic}[1]
\Procedure{BuildDPHalf}{$S_{\text{half}},\ \text{target}$}
    \State $\mathcal{H}[0] \gets (\text{len}(S_{\text{half}}),\,0)$ \Comment{empty subset sentinel}
    \For{$i \gets \text{len}(S_{\text{half}})-1$ \textbf{downto} $0$}
        \State $\text{newStates} \gets \{\}$
        \ForAll{$(\text{sum},\,(\text{idx},\text{cnt})) \in \mathcal{H}$}
            \State $\text{newSum} \gets \text{sum} + S_{\text{half}}[i]$
            \If{$\text{newSum} > \text{target}$}
                \State \textbf{continue} \Comment{ignore sums that already exceed the target}
            \EndIf
            \State $\text{newCnt} \gets \text{cnt} + 1$
            \If{$\text{newSum} \notin \mathcal{H}$}
                \State $\text{newStates}[\text{newSum}] \gets (i,\,\text{newCnt})$  \Comment{insert new entry}
            \Else
            \If{$\mathcal{H}[\text{newSum}].\text{cnt} > \text{newCnt}$}
                \State $\mathcal{\text{newStates}}[\text{newSum}] \gets (\mathcal{H}[\text{newSum}].\text{idx},\,\text{newCnt})$ \Comment{better witness found}
               
            \EndIf
            \EndIf
        \EndFor
        \State $\mathcal{H} \gets \mathcal{H} \cup \text{newStates}$ \Comment{batch insert and overwrite if same sum}
    \EndFor
    \State \Return $\mathcal{H}$
\EndProcedure
\end{algorithmic}
\end{algorithm}


\paragraph{Complexity Analysis.}
Let $U$ denote the number of unique achievable subset sums in a given half. The DP hash map construction takes $O(U N)$ time and $O(U)$ space, which is highly efficient when $U \ll 2^{N/2}$. In the worst case, $U$ can reach $2^{N/2}$, but for inputs with many collisions, the practical complexity is dramatically reduced.

\subsubsection*{2.4 Subset Reconstruction from DP States}
\label{sec:reconstructsubsets}

Once the dynamic programming tables for each partition are constructed, all valid subsets corresponding to a particular sum can be reconstructed efficiently by recursively traversing the recorded state information. The reconstruction procedure systematically explores inclusion and exclusion of each element, using the DP table both to ensure correctness and to enable aggressive pruning.

\begin{algorithm}[H]
\caption{\textsc{ReconstructHalfSubsets}: enumerate all subsets inside a partition that realise \texttt{targetRem}}
\label{alg:reconstructHalf}
\begin{algorithmic}[1]
\Procedure{ReconstructHalfSubsets}{$\texttt{part},\ \texttt{pos},\ \texttt{targetRem},\ \texttt{dp},\ \texttt{partial}$}
    \If{$\texttt{targetRem}=0$}
    \newline
        
        \Comment{found a complete subset$\{\texttt{partial}$}
        
    \EndIf
    \If{$\texttt{pos}=|\texttt{part}|$ \textbf{or} $\texttt{targetRem}<0$}
        \State \Return $\emptyset$
    \EndIf
    \State $($\texttt{startIdx},\,\texttt{minCnt}$) \gets \texttt{dp}[\texttt{targetRem}]$
    \If{$\texttt{startIdx} \ge \texttt{pos+1}$}   \Comment{element at \texttt{pos} may be skipped}
    \\
        \Call{ReconstructHalfSubsets}{$\texttt{part},\ \texttt{pos}+1,\ \texttt{targetRem},\ \texttt{dp},\ \texttt{partial}$}
    \EndIf
    \If{$\texttt{targetRem} \ge \texttt{part}[\texttt{pos}]$}
        \State $($\texttt{nextIdx},\,\texttt{nextCnt}$) \gets \texttt{dp}[\texttt{targetRem}-\texttt{part}[\texttt{pos}]]$
        \If{$\texttt{nextIdx} \ge \texttt{pos+1}$}  \Comment{element at \texttt{pos} can be taken}
            
            \Call{ReconstructHalfSubsets}
                 {$\texttt{part},\ \texttt{pos}+1,\ \texttt{targetRem}-\texttt{part}[\texttt{pos}],\ \texttt{dp},\ \texttt{partial}\cup\{\texttt{part}[\texttt{pos}]\}$}
        \EndIf
    \EndIf
    \State \Return  
\EndProcedure
\end{algorithmic}
\end{algorithm}


This procedure guarantees completeness and non-redundancy in the set of reconstructed subsets. By leveraging the minimal state information retained in $\mathcal{H}$, the search avoids redundant branches and respects all constraints imposed during the DP construction.

\subsubsection*{2.5 Meet-in-the-Middle Subset Enumeration Algorithm}

The full enumeration algorithm operates by partitioning the set $S$, building DP tables for each half, and combining compatible subset pairs whose sums are complementary with respect to the target $T$.

\begin{algorithm}[H]
\caption{Meet-in-the-Middle Subset Enumeration}
\label{alg:meet_in_middle}
\begin{algorithmic}[1]
\Procedure{EnumerateSubsets}{$S$, $T$}
    \State $(S_L, S_R) \gets$ \Call{Partition}{$S$}
    \State $\mathcal{H}_L \gets$ \Call{BuildDPHalf}{$S_L$}
    \State $\mathcal{H}_R \gets$ \Call{BuildDPHalf}{$S_R$}
    \State $\text{solutions} \gets \emptyset$
    \For{each $(\text{sum}_L, \cdot) \in \mathcal{H}_L$}
        \State $\text{sum}_R \gets T - \text{sum}_L$
        \If{$\text{sum}_R \in \mathcal{H}_R$}
            \State $\text{left\_subsets} \gets$ \Call{ReconstructSubsets}{$S_L, 0, \text{sum}_L, \mathcal{H}_L, \emptyset$}
            \State $\text{right\_subsets} \gets$ \Call{ReconstructSubsets}{$S_R, 0, \text{sum}_R, \mathcal{H}_R, \emptyset$}
            \For{each $L \in \text{left\_subsets}$, $R \in \text{right\_subsets}$}
                \State $\text{solutions} \gets \text{solutions} \cup \{L \cup R\}$
            \EndFor
        \EndIf
    \EndFor
    \State \Return $\text{solutions}$
\EndProcedure
\end{algorithmic}
\end{algorithm}


\subsubsection*{2.6 Subset Size Limitation via Minimum Count Tracking}

In the meet-in-the-middle framework, we partition the input set $S$ into two disjoint subsets $S_L$ and $S_R$ of sizes $n_L$ and $n_R$ respectively, where $n_L + n_R = N$. A critical optimization involves imposing size constraints on the subsets enumerated within each half.

\textbf{Size Constraint Strategy:} During dynamic programming table construction, we track the minimum number of elements required to achieve each sum (the \textit{min\_count} parameter). By maintaining this information, we restrict enumeration to subsets of size at most $\lceil n_L/2 \rceil$ in the left half and $\lceil n_R/2 \rceil$ in the right half.

% This constraint provides benefits:
% \begin{enumerate}
%     \item \textbf{Computational Efficiency:} Reduces the state space from $O(2^{n_L/2})$ to $O(\binom{n_L}{\lfloor n_L/2 \rfloor})$ per half
%     \item \textbf{Algorithmic Completeness:} Maintains exhaustive coverage through complementary subset logic
% \end{enumerate}

\subsubsection*{2.7 Complementary Subset Enumeration}

The size limitation strategy relies on the mathematical principle that every subset has a unique complement, and their union covers all possible combinations.We formalize this through the following lemmas:

  

\begin{lemma}[Complete Coverage via Complements]
\label{lemma:complete_coverage}
By enumerating all subsets of size at most $\lceil n_L/2 \rceil$ in each half, we achieve complete coverage of all possible subset sums through four enumeration patterns:
\begin{align}
\text{Pattern 1:} \quad &L \cup R &&\text{(direct subsets)} \\
\text{Pattern 2:} \quad &L^c \cup R^c &&\text{(both complements)} \\
\text{Pattern 3:} \quad &L \cup R^c &&\text{(left subset, right complement)} \\
\text{Pattern 4:} \quad &L^c \cup R &&\text{(left complement, right subset)}
\end{align}
\end{lemma}

\begin{proof}[Proof]
Consider any target subset $X \subseteq S$ with $X = X_L \cup X_R$ where $X_L = X \cap S_L$ and $X_R = X \cap S_R$. Without loss of generality, assume $|X_L| \leq \lceil n_L/2 \rceil$. Then either:
\begin{itemize}
    \item $|X_R| \leq \lceil n_R/2 \rceil$: Covered by Pattern 1
    \item $|X_R| > \lceil n_R/2 \rceil$: Then $|X_R^c| < \lceil n_R/2 \rceil$, covered by Pattern 3
\end{itemize}
The case $|X_L| > \lceil n_L/2 \rceil$ is handled symmetrically using Patterns 2 and 4.
\end{proof}

\subsubsection*{2.8 Implementation of Complementary Logic}
\paragraph{Complement Logic and Bounded Duplication.}
The routine in Alg.~\ref{alg:mitm_complement} enumerates every feasible subset
by combining witnesses from the two DP tables in four disjoint ways:
\[
\begin{aligned}
\text{(i)}\;&L             \cup  R, &
\text{(ii)}\;&L^c          \cup  R^c,\\
\text{(iii)}\;&L           \cup  R^c,&
\text{(iv)}\;&L^c          \cup  R .
\end{aligned}
\]
Here $L$ (resp.~$R$) is a subset reconstructed in its own half, and $L^c$
(resp.~$R^c$) denotes its complement within $S_L$ (resp.~$S_R$).
Enumerating all four patterns is essential for completeness once
per-half subset sizes are capped at $\lceil n_L/2 \rceil$ and
$\lceil n_R/2 \rceil$.

\smallskip
\textbf{Why duplicates may arise.}  
During DP construction we always keep the \emph{currently smallest} witness
length for a sum.  
If a shorter witness is discovered at an earlier index $i$,
the table now claims that this shorter length is reachable
\emph{starting at~$i$}, even though the actual witness may still begin at some
$j>i$.  
Consequently, reconstruction invoked at~$i$ may first fail with the optimistic
length and then succeed with the older (longer) length stored deeper in the
call stack, causing the same numeric subset sum to be generated twice within
that half.

\paragraph{Redundancy Bound: why \boldmath$4$ and no more.}
Let \(X\subseteq S\) be any subset produced by Algorithm~\ref{alg:mitm_complement}.  
Write
\[
s_L=\sum_{x\in X\cap S_L}x, 
\qquad
s_R=\sum_{x\in X\cap S_R}x,
\qquad
s_L^{c}= \Sigma_L-s_L,
\qquad
s_R^{c}= \Sigma_R-s_R ,
\]
where \(\Sigma_L=\sum_{x\in S_L}x\) and \(\Sigma_R=\sum_{x\in S_R}x\).
The algorithm merges witnesses from the two DP tables only for the four
\emph{complement pairs}
\[
(s_L,s_R),\;
(s_L,s_R^{c}),\;
(s_L^{c},s_R),\;
(s_L^{c},s_R^{c}),
\tag{$\star$}
\]
corresponding to the four logical patterns  
\(L\cup R,\;L\cup R^{c},\;L^{c}\cup R,\;L^{c}\cup R^{c}\).

\begin{enumerate}[label=\roman*.]
\item \textbf{Determinism within a pair.}  
      For any numeric pair in $(\star)$, the call
      \textsc{ReconstructSubsets} traverses the DP table deterministically, so
      a concrete subset consistent with that pair is emitted \emph{once} and
      only once.

\item \textbf{Exactly four relevant pairs.}  
      The sums \((s_L,s_R)\) uniquely identify \(X\);
      replacing either component by its complement corresponds to swapping the
      subset/complement taken from that half of the input.
      No other numeric pair can realise \(X\), and each of the four pairs in
      $(\star)$ maps to a \emph{distinct} pattern.
\end{enumerate}

Hence \(X\) can be generated at most one time per pattern, yielding an
absolute duplication limit of \(4\).
This constant-factor redundancy is negligible for asymptotic analysis and
can be removed, if desired, by a final duplicate-filtering pass that scans
the output once.
 

\begin{algorithm}
\caption{Meet-in-the-Middle Subset Sum Enumeration with Explicit Complement Handling}
\label{alg:mitm_complement}
\begin{algorithmic}[1]
\Procedure{EnumerateWithComplements}{$S_L$, $S_R$, $T$}
    \State $\mathcal{H}_L \gets$ \Call{AllSubsetSumsAndDPStates}{$S_L$}
    \State $\mathcal{H}_R \gets$ \Call{AllSubsetSumsAndDPStates}{$S_R$}
    \State $\sigma_L \gets \sum_{x \in S_L} x$, $\sigma_R \gets \sum_{x \in S_R} x$
    \State $\text{solutions} \gets \{\}$
    
    \For{each $s_L$ in $\mathcal{H}_L.\text{keys}()$}
        \State $s_R \gets T - s_L$
        \If{$s_R \in \mathcal{H}_R$}
            \State $\text{left\_subsets} \gets$ \Call{ReconstructSubsets}{$S_L$, $s_L$, $\mathcal{H}_L$}
            \State $\text{right\_subsets} \gets$ \Call{ReconstructSubsets}{$S_R$, $s_R$, $\mathcal{H}_R$}
            \For{each $L \in \text{left\_subsets}$, $R \in \text{right\_subsets}$}
                \State $\text{solutions} \gets \text{solutions} \cup \{L \cup R\}$
            \EndFor
        \EndIf
        
        \State $s_R' \gets T - (\sigma_L - s_L)$
        \If{$s_R' \in \mathcal{H}_R$}
            \State $\text{left\_subsets} \gets$ \Call{ReconstructSubsets}{$S_L$, $s_L$, $\mathcal{H}_L$}
            \State $\text{right\_subsets} \gets$ \Call{ReconstructSubsets}{$S_R$, $s_R'$, $\mathcal{H}_R$}
            \For{each $L \in \text{left\_subsets}$, $R \in \text{right\_subsets}$}
                \State $\text{solutions} \gets \text{solutions} \cup \{L \cup (S_R \setminus R)\}$
            \EndFor
        \EndIf
        
        \State $s_L' \gets \sigma_L - (T - s_R)$
        \If{$s_L' \in \mathcal{H}_L$}
            \State $\text{left\_subsets} \gets$ \Call{ReconstructSubsets}{$S_L$, $s_L'$, $\mathcal{H}_L$}
            \State $\text{right\_subsets} \gets$ \Call{ReconstructSubsets}{$S_R$, $s_R$, $\mathcal{H}_R$}
            \For{each $L \in \text{left\_subsets}$, $R \in \text{right\_subsets}$}
                \State $\text{solutions} \gets \text{solutions} \cup \{(S_L \setminus L) \cup R\}$
            \EndFor
        \EndIf
        
        \State $s_L'' \gets \sigma_L - s_L$, $s_R'' \gets \sigma_R - s_R$
        \If{$s_L'' \in \mathcal{H}_L$ and $s_R'' \in \mathcal{H}_R$}
            \State $\text{left\_subsets} \gets$ \Call{ReconstructSubsets}{$S_L$, $s_L''$, $\mathcal{H}_L$}
            \State $\text{right\_subsets} \gets$ \Call{ReconstructSubsets}{$S_R$, $s_R''$, $\mathcal{H}_R$}
            \For{each $L \in \text{left\_subsets}$, $R \in \text{right\_subsets}$}
                \State $\text{solutions} \gets \text{solutions} \cup \{(S_L \setminus L) \cup (S_R \setminus R)\}$
            \EndFor
        \EndIf
    \EndFor
    
    \State \Return $\text{solutions}$
\EndProcedure

\end{algorithmic}
\end{algorithm}

